{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/605"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.18,0.08,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101734"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35296"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101734"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of fever, fatigue, general malaise and sore throat. He denies weight loss, loss of appetite, cough, dyspnoea, or any abdominal symptoms. He has just returned from a trip to Brazil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is lymphadenopathy of the anterior chain bilaterally. His left tonsil is covered in white exudate. The chest is clear on auscultation. There is fullness in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monospot test","Throat swab","Thick and thin blood film","Respiratory viral PCR","Quantiferon gold test"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe probable diagnosis based on the clinical picture is infectious mononucleosis (IM), known colloquially as glandular fever. A while exudate on the tonsil suggests a bacterial or viral infection. The abdominal fullness would be consistent with an enlarged spleen. The heterophile antibody test (aka \u003Cstrong\u003EMonospot test\u003C/strong\u003E) is the first-line investigation for confirmation of IM. The causative agent in IM is the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV). EBV serology is usually not required, as most patients are heterophile positive. However, EBV-specific antibodies may be tested in patients with suspected infectious mononucleosis who have a negative heterophile test. Patients in the first week of the clinical course may have a false negative Monospot in up to 25% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethroat swab\u003C/strong\u003E for bacterial culture would be useful if bacterial pharyngitis was suspected, but the clinical picture is more consistent with IM.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the patient has recently returned from Brazil, a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethick and thin blood film\u003C/strong\u003E to test for malaria is not the most appropriate first-line investigation. Malaria should be considered in any febrile returning traveller, but the presence of exudative pharyngitis and lymphadenopathy is more suggestive of IM. If the Monospot test is negative and symptoms persist, further investigations including blood films for malaria may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory viral PCR\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if the patient had prominent respiratory symptoms, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EQuantiferon gold test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect latent tuberculosis infection. While TB should be considered in patients with prolonged fever and weight loss, especially after travel to endemic areas, the acute onset and clinical features in this case are not typical for TB.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The monospot test can have a significant false negative rate if performed within the first week of onset of symptoms suggestive of infectious mononucleosis.","Thick and thin blood films are the gold standard for diagnosing malaria in returning travellers with fever."],"references":["Evans AS, Niederman JC, Cenabre LC, et al. A prospective evaluation of heterophile and Epstein-Barr virus-specific IgM antibody tests in clinical and subclinical infectious mononucleosis: Specificity and sensitivity of the tests and persistence of antibody. J Infect Dis 1975; 132:546.","Ebell MH, Call M, Shinholser J, Gardner J. Does This Patient Have Infectious Mononucleosis?: The Rational Clinical Examination Systematic Review. JAMA 2016; 315:1502."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"605"}},"stemMedia":